We should probably just change this to a regular if / else block. I don't know why co-worker thought this was a more straight forward way to do this. Making it PEP8 doesn't really fix the underlying clarity issue.

```
if minutes == 1:
    return _("1 minute")
elif minutes > 1:
    return _("%d minutes") % minutes
...
...
```

I guess i'm a little confused on what exactly a canonical representation is. Isn't it a 20byte long string of bytes? @carver suggested in the last pr the below implementation and "We don't need to test the canonical-ness of bytes, it's clearly not. "
```python
def is_canonical_address(address):
    if not is_string(address) or not is_hex(address):
        return False
    elif not is_address(hexstr=address):
        return False
    else:
        return address == to_canonical_address(hexstr=address)
```
The test case from the readme passes now but breaks if I add `if not is_string(address) or not is_hex(address):`
